    `},{id:"def-ordered-set",title:"Definition 1.5 (Ordered Set)",statement:"An **order** on a set $S$ is a relation $<$ such that: (1) For any $x, y \\in S$, exactly one holds: $x < y$, $x = y$, or $y < x$. (2) If $x < y$ and $y < z$, then $x < z$ (transitivity).",sectionId:1,sectionTitle:"Ordered Sets",category:"Ordered Sets",type:"definition"},{id:"def-upper-bound",title:"Definition 1.7 (Upper Bound)",statement:"Let $S$ be an ordered set and $E \\subset S$. If there exists $\\beta \\in S$ such that $x \\leq \\beta$ for all $x \\in E$, we say $E$ is **bounded above** and $\\beta$ is an **upper bound** of $E$.",sectionId:1,sectionTitle:"Ordered Sets",category:"Ordered Sets",type:"definition"},{id:"def-supremum",title:"Definition 1.8 (Supremum)",statement:"Let $S$ be an ordered set and $E \\subset S$ be bounded above. If there exists $\\alpha \\in S$ such that: (1) $\\alpha$ is an upper bound of $E$, and (2) $\\gamma < \\alpha \\Rightarrow \\gamma$ is not an upper bound of $E$, then $\\alpha$ is called the **least upper bound** or **supremum** of $E$, written $\\alpha = \\sup E$.",sectionId:1,sectionTitle:"Ordered Sets",category:"Ordered Sets",type:"definition"},{id:"def-lub-property",title:"Definition 1.10 (Least Upper Bound Property)",statement:"An ordered set $S$ has the **least upper bound property** if every nonempty subset of $S$ that is bounded above has a supremum in $S$.",sectionId:1,sectionTitle:"Ordered Sets",category:"Ordered Sets",type:"definition"},{id:"thm-1.11-lub-glb",title:"Theorem 1.11 (LUB implies GLB)",statement:"If $S$ has the least upper bound property, then $S$ also has the greatest lower bound property.",sectionId:1,sectionTitle:"Ordered Sets",category:"Ordered Sets",type:"theorem",hasProof:!0,proof:`
